(8, 2, E'# CaseGate: Walk-In Intake and Case Management for Small Law Firms\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nCaseGate is a structured intake and case lifecycle management platform built for small law firms with 3–8 attorneys. The central problem it solves is the chaotic, paper-heavy walk-in consultation process that characterizes most small firm operations—potential clients arrive, fill out handwritten forms, wait without updates, and frequently fall through the cracks due to inconsistent follow-up. CaseGate digitizes this process end-to-end: digital intake forms on a lobby tablet, automatic case assignment based on attorney specialization and availability, templated follow-up sequences, and a conflict-of-interest check against existing clients. By systematizing intake, CaseGate helps small firms convert 20–35% more consultations into retained clients. Priced at $149/month per firm. Target: 600 firms, $1.07M ARR by Month 24.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Small law firms (2–9 attorneys) in US | ~75,000 | ABA Profile of the Legal Profession 2024 |\n| UK law firms with fewer than 10 solicitors | ~9,800 | SRA Regulated Community Report 2023 |\n| Average consultation-to-retainer conversion | 38% | Clio Legal Trends Report 2024 |\n| Firms citing "intake inefficiency" as top problem | 61% | Clio survey, n=4,200 firms |\n| Revenue per retained client (avg, small firm) | $3,400 | Clio Legal Trends 2024 |\n| Annual revenue loss from poor intake follow-up | ~$42,000/firm | Estimated 12 lost clients × $3,400 |\n| Willingness to pay for intake software | 55% at $100–$200/mo | Clio market study |\n| TAM (US small firms) | ~$135M | 75K firms × $150 ARPU |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Intake Features | Case Management | Price | Weakness |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Clio Grow | Excellent intake | Basic | $109/mo/user | Per-user pricing; expensive for 5+ attorneys |\n| MyCase | Good | Yes | $49–$89/mo/user | Per-user; complex for small firms |\n| Lawmatics | Excellent CRM/intake | No case mgmt | $199–$499/mo | No case assignment or follow-up automation |\n| PracticePanther | Basic intake | Yes | $49/mo/user | Generic; weak intake UX |\n| Filevine | Enterprise | Yes | $300+/mo | Over-built for 3–8 attorney firms |\n| **CaseGate** | Best-in-class intake | Lightweight | $149/mo flat | New entrant |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Patricia, 52, Managing Partner, 5-Attorney Family Law Firm, Phoenix AZ**\nPatricia''s firm sees 30–40 walk-in and same-day appointment consultations monthly. The current process: receptionist fills out a paper form, photocopies a government ID, assigns the next available attorney manually, and sends a follow-up email from Gmail 3–5 days later—if she remembers. Patricia has lost prospective clients who chose competing firms after receiving no follow-up for 2 weeks. She needs a system that ensures every consultation is logged, assigned, and followed up within 48 hours automatically.\n\n**Persona 2 — David, 44, Senior Partner, 3-Attorney Immigration Law Practice, Houston TX**\nDavid''s boutique immigration practice handles highly sensitive cases. The intake challenge is twofold: gathering complex case-type information at intake (visa type, country of origin, urgency) and performing conflict checks before a consultation takes place. He currently runs conflict checks manually in a spreadsheet. An automated conflict-of-interest check against all existing clients would save 20 minutes per new consultation and protect the firm from malpractice exposure.\n\n**Persona 3 — Helen, 37, Solo Managing Partner with 4 Associates, London UK**\nHelen''s personal injury firm receives referrals from medical providers and word-of-mouth. Intake forms are emailed as PDFs—she receives 15–20 incomplete submissions weekly, requiring manual follow-up to collect missing information. She wants intake forms that validate completeness, collect supporting documents digitally, and auto-assign to the associate with the lightest current caseload.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Digital Intake Form | Configurable per practice area; runs on lobby tablet or shareable link |\n| P0 | Conflict of Interest Check | Auto-searches existing client database for name + opposing party matches |\n| P0 | Attorney Assignment Engine | Routes new cases to attorneys by specialization, availability, and current caseload |\n| P0 | Automated Follow-Up | Templated SMS + email sequences at 24hr, 72hr, 1-week post-consultation |\n| P0 | Case Status Dashboard | Real-time view of all intake cases: new, assigned, consulted, retained, declined |\n| P1 | Document Collection | Intake form prompts for ID, relevant documents; secure upload portal |\n| P1 | Appointment Scheduler | Self-booking link for remote consultations; Zoom/Teams integration |\n| P1 | Retainer Agreement | E-sign retainer via DocuSign or HelloSign at conversion |\n| P1 | Lead Source Tracking | Record referral source per intake; track conversion by source |\n| P2 | Practice Area Analytics | Conversion rate, time-to-consult, time-to-retainer per practice area |\n| P2 | Client Portal | Secure status updates for prospective clients awaiting assignment |\n| P2 | Court Date Integration | Import hearing dates from state court systems (California, Texas, Florida first) |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Backend**: Go 1.23 + Echo v4 REST API. PostgreSQL 16 for all relational data. Redis for session management and job queue.\n\n**Conflict Check Engine**: PostgreSQL full-text search (tsvector/tsquery) across client names, opposing party names, and related entities. Fuzzy matching via pg_trgm for name variations (O''Brien / OBrien). Returns conflict match within 200ms.\n\n**Intake Forms**: JSON-schema-driven form builder; practice area templates define required fields and document types. Forms rendered client-side via React; submissions stored encrypted at rest (AES-256).\n\n**Document Storage**: AWS S3 with server-side encryption. Presigned upload URLs (5-minute TTL); files never pass through application server.\n\n**Follow-Up Engine**: Temporal.io workflow orchestration for reliable, durable follow-up sequences with attorney override capability.\n\n**Frontend**: Next.js 14 + TailwindCSS. Tablet-optimized intake view (full-screen kiosk mode for lobby deployment).\n\n**Security**: SOC 2 Type II target at 18 months. TLS 1.3 in transit. ABA Model Rules for Technology Competence compliance documentation provided to all subscribers.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Attorneys | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Essentials | $149/mo | Up to 5 attorneys | Intake forms, conflict check, assignment, follow-up |\n| Growth | $249/mo | Up to 10 attorneys | + document collection, retainer e-sign, analytics |\n| Enterprise | $449/mo | Unlimited | + court date integration, client portal, API access |\n\nAt 600 firms: 65% Essentials, 30% Growth, 5% Enterprise = $58K + $45K + $13K = $116K MRR = $1.39M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Digital intake forms (5 practice area templates), case dashboard, basic assignment |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Conflict of interest check, automated follow-up sequences, appointment scheduler |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Document collection portal, retainer e-sign, lead source tracking |\n| M4 | Months 7–9 | Practice area analytics, client portal, API for CLIO integration, mobile app |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M4 | M8 | M24 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying firms | 60 | 200 | 600 |\n| MRR | $9,500 | $32,000 | $116,000 |\n| Consultation-to-retainer conversion lift | +10% | +18% | +28% |\n| Follow-up completion rate | > 92% | > 96% | > 98% |\n| Conflict check false-negative rate | < 0.1% | < 0.05% | < 0.02% |\n| Time from walk-in to assignment (median) | < 5 min | < 3 min | < 2 min |\n| NPS | ≥ 45 | ≥ 55 | ≥ 65 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Bar association ethics compliance concerns | High | Very High | Legal counsel review of ABA Model Rules 1.1 (technology), 1.6 (confidentiality); publish compliance white paper |\n| Attorneys resistant to software adoption | High | High | Champion-first sales: target tech-comfortable associate, not managing partner; provide ROI calculator |\n| Conflict check false negatives expose firm to malpractice | Low | Very High | Multi-layer fuzzy matching; attorney override confirmation required before proceeding |\n| Data breach of sensitive client information | Low | Very High | Penetration test pre-launch; cyber insurance requirement; incident response plan |\n| Integration with Clio/MyCase required by enterprise buyers | Medium | Medium | REST API in M4 roadmap; Zapier integration as interim bridge |\n', '[{"step":"market_entry","decision":"Target family law and immigration practices first","reason":"These practice areas have highest walk-in consultation volume and least sophisticated intake tools; fastest path to case studies"},{"step":"conflict_check","decision":"Build custom PostgreSQL full-text search vs. third-party API","reason":"Third-party conflict check APIs cost $0.50–$2.00 per check; at 40 checks/month per firm, margins evaporate; pg_trgm is 95% as accurate at zero marginal cost"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Flat firm pricing over per-user","reason":"Per-user pricing creates resistance in 5+ attorney firms; flat pricing is predictable and aligns with how law firms budget software"},{"step":"compliance","decision":"Publish ABA compliance white paper before launch","reason":"Bar associations can censure attorneys for using non-compliant technology; proactive compliance documentation reduces sales friction significantly"},{"step":"document_storage","decision":"AWS S3 with presigned URLs, never proxy documents","reason":"Client intake documents include government IDs and financial records; passing through application server increases attack surface and liability"}]',
 'submitted', 51, NOW() - INTERVAL '35 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '36 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '35 days'),

(8, 14, E'# IntakeIQ: Intelligent Case Intake Platform for Growing Law Firms\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nIntakeIQ transforms how small law firms convert prospective clients into retained cases by making the intake and triage process intelligent, fast, and professionally branded. The platform''s differentiated approach is its "smart triage" engine: prospective clients complete a guided intake questionnaire that dynamically adapts questions based on their responses (a personal injury inquiry evolves differently than a business dispute). The system scores case strength and value potential on a 1–10 scale based on responses, enabling attorneys to prioritize high-value consultations and deprioritize weak cases before investing attorney time. This saves the average 5-attorney firm 8–12 attorney hours per month previously spent on unqualified consultations. Priced at $199/month per firm. Target: 500 firms, $1.19M ARR by Month 24.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| US law firms with 2–9 attorneys | ~75,000 | ABA 2024 |\n| Average unqualified consultations per month | 11 (of ~35) | Clio Legal Trends 2024 |\n| Attorney hourly billing rate (small firm avg) | $285/hr | Thomson Reuters 2024 Legal Tracker |\n| Monthly cost of unqualified consultations | ~$3,135 | 11 × 1hr × $285 |\n| Firms with no intake software (paper/email) | 58% | Clio survey 2024 |\n| Intake software average ROI (first year) | 4.2x | Lawmatics Customer Study |\n| Legal software market (SMB) CAGR | 11.4% | Grand View Research 2024 |\n| SAM (US, 2–9 attorney firms) | ~$150M | 75K × $166 avg ARPU |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Smart Triage | Case Scoring | Conflict Check | Price |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Clio Grow | No | No | Basic | $109/mo/user |\n| Lawmatics | Partial (conditional logic) | No | No | $199–$499/mo |\n| Intake123 | Basic | No | No | $49–$149/mo |\n| CARET Legal | No | No | Yes | $89/mo/user |\n| Smokeball | No | No | Yes | $99–$149/mo/user |\n| **IntakeIQ** | Yes, adaptive logic | Yes, AI-scored | Yes | $199/mo flat |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Robert, 49, Managing Partner, 6-Attorney Personal Injury Firm, Atlanta GA**\nRobert''s firm operates on contingency: they only earn if they win. Selecting the right cases is existential. He currently screens intakes over the phone—a process consuming 45 minutes of a paralegal''s time and 15 minutes of his own per potential case. An intake system that pre-qualifies cases against his firm''s minimum criteria (injury severity, liability clarity, insurance coverage) before any attorney touches the file would transform his firm''s economics.\n\n**Persona 2 — Susan, 41, Partner, 4-Attorney Business & Commercial Law Firm, Boston MA**\nSusan handles business disputes, contract reviews, and M&A for small businesses. Her intake challenge is different: she needs to capture enough detail at intake to provide a meaningful quote. Current intake forms miss 40% of required information, requiring callbacks. She wants dynamic forms that ask follow-up questions based on case type (contract dispute → which contract? → value? → breach type?).\n\n**Persona 3 — Connor, 36, Solicitor-Principal, 5-Solicitor Personal Injury Practice, Dublin IE**\nConnor operates in the Irish market with Irish GDPR (GDPR applied by Irish DPC) requirements. He needs a platform that stores all client data on EU infrastructure, provides GDPR-compliant consent management at intake, and generates DSAR-compliant data export on request. His previous US-hosted tool caused a DPC enquiry he narrowly resolved.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Adaptive Intake Questionnaire | Dynamic question logic: responses trigger follow-up questions by practice area |\n| P0 | Case Strength Scoring | AI model scores 1–10 on case value, liability clarity, damages potential |\n| P0 | Conflict of Interest Engine | Searches all parties, opposing counsel, related entities; flags matches |\n| P0 | Attorney Routing | Assign by specialization, score threshold, current caseload |\n| P0 | Automated Follow-Up | Multi-channel (email, SMS, portal) sequences with attorney overrides |\n| P1 | Consultation Scheduler | Calendar integration; video (Zoom/Teams) and in-person booking |\n| P1 | Document Upload Portal | Drag-and-drop; accepts photos (accident scenes), PDFs (medical records) |\n| P1 | Retainer Generation | Auto-populate retainer agreement from intake data; e-sign |\n| P1 | Referral Partner Portal | Referring attorneys or providers view referral status without firm credentials |\n| P2 | Conversion Analytics | Funnel: inquiries → scored → consulted → retained; segmented by source |\n| P2 | GDPR Compliance Module | EU data residency, consent management, DSAR export, DPA template |\n| P2 | Mobile Attorney App | Review and act on new intakes from iOS/Android |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Case Scoring Engine**: Logistic regression model trained on ~8,000 anonymized historical intake records (aggregated from beta firms, opt-in). Features: case type, injury/damage severity indicators, liability admission, insurance presence, jurisdiction. Model serialized to ONNX; inference in Go < 50ms.\n\n**Adaptive Form Engine**: JSON-schema form definition with conditional logic (jsonata expressions). Form state managed client-side (React); partial submissions auto-saved every 30 seconds.\n\n**Backend**: Go 1.23 + Echo v4. PostgreSQL 16 (US region: AWS us-east-1; EU region: AWS eu-west-1 for GDPR). Redis for sessions and queues.\n\n**Communication**: Twilio (SMS) + AWS SES (email). Temporal.io for durable follow-up workflows with attorney override support.\n\n**Document Management**: AWS S3 (region-matched), presigned upload URLs, virus scanning via ClamAV on receipt.\n\n**Frontend**: Next.js 14 App Router + TailwindCSS. Tablet kiosk mode for lobby intake.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Features |\n|---|---|---|\n| Core | $199/mo | Up to 5 attorneys, adaptive intake, scoring, conflict check, follow-up |\n| Scale | $349/mo | Up to 12 attorneys, referral portal, analytics, document portal |\n| Enterprise | Custom | Unlimited attorneys, GDPR module, API, white-label |\n\nAt 500 firms (70% Core, 25% Scale, 5% Enterprise ~$700/mo): $69.6K + $43.6K + $17.5K = $130K MRR = $1.56M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–3 | Adaptive intake forms (3 practice areas), case dashboard, attorney assignment, basic follow-up |\n| M2 | Months 4–5 | Case scoring engine v1, conflict of interest check, consultation scheduler |\n| M3 | Months 6–7 | Document upload portal, retainer generation + e-sign, referral partner portal |\n| M4 | Months 8–10 | Conversion analytics, GDPR module, mobile app, Clio/MyCase integration |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M4 | M10 | M24 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying firms | 50 | 200 | 500 |\n| MRR | $10,500 | $43,000 | $130,000 |\n| Case scoring accuracy (vs. attorney manual rating) | > 78% | > 84% | > 89% |\n| Unqualified consultation reduction | 25% | 35% | 45% |\n| Time from inquiry to scored + assigned | < 8 min | < 5 min | < 3 min |\n| Retainer conversion rate improvement | +15% | +25% | +35% |\n| Net Promoter Score | ≥ 42 | ≥ 55 | ≥ 65 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| AI case scoring biased against minority plaintiffs | Medium | Very High | Regular bias audits; attorney always final decision; model explainability required |\n| Bar ethics concerns about AI in legal intake | High | High | Position as "triage assistant, not legal advice"; publish ethics opinion analysis per state bar |\n| Training data insufficient for accurate scoring | High | Medium | Start with 3 practice areas with most data; expand model as user base grows |\n| GDPR non-compliance for EU expansion | Medium | High | EU data residency from day one (AWS eu-west-1); DPO consultation before EU launch |\n| Competing with Clio on brand trust | High | Medium | Target firms specifically frustrated with Clio''s per-user pricing; case study ROI marketing |\n', '[{"step":"differentiation","decision":"AI case scoring as primary value prop","reason":"No competitor offers automated case strength scoring; this directly addresses contingency firm pain of unqualified consultations worth $3K+/month in wasted attorney time"},{"step":"model_approach","decision":"Logistic regression over LLM for case scoring","reason":"Logistic regression on structured intake fields is explainable, auditable, and defensible to bar ethics boards; LLM scoring is a black box with malpractice exposure"},{"step":"geo_strategy","decision":"Launch US first, EU module in M4","reason":"GDPR compliance requires additional legal infrastructure; US market alone is $150M SAM; EU module adds TAM without delaying US launch"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$199 flat over per-user model","reason":"Clio Grow at $109/user becomes $545/month for 5 attorneys; $199 flat undercuts by 63% while delivering superior triage features"},{"step":"data_strategy","decision":"Aggregate anonymized beta firm data for model training","reason":"Per-firm models would require 1,000+ intakes to be accurate; pooled anonymized data achieves sufficient sample size with 15–20 beta firms"}]',
 'submitted', 44, NOW() - INTERVAL '32 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '33 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '32 days'),

(8, 21, E'# FirstContact: Streamlined Intake & Follow-Up for Small Law Offices\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nFirstContact is a no-frills, fast-to-deploy intake and follow-up system that prioritizes time-to-value over feature depth. The platform is built on the insight that 70% of small law firms with intake problems don''t need AI or sophisticated CRM—they need three things done reliably: (1) walk-in client information captured digitally and consistently, (2) the right attorney notified immediately, and (3) a follow-up reminder sent automatically within 48 hours. FirstContact delivers exactly these three things with a setup time under 20 minutes, no IT involvement, and pricing that fits a solo-managing-partner''s budget at $79/month. The deliberate simplicity is the product. Target: 1,200 firms, $1.14M ARR by Month 20, with a land-and-expand motion toward a fuller case management suite.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| US law firms 2–4 attorneys | ~48,000 | ABA 2024 (subset of small firm data) |\n| US law firms 5–9 attorneys | ~27,000 | ABA 2024 |\n| Avg. intake consultations per month (2–4 atty) | 18 | Clio Legal Trends 2024 |\n| Follow-up failure rate (no system) | 43% | Clio survey |\n| Revenue lost per missed follow-up | ~$3,400 | Avg. retainer value |\n| Monthly revenue loss per firm (follow-up) | ~$26,000 | 43% × 18 × $3,400 (theoretical max) |\n| Firms willing to pay < $100/mo for intake tool | 67% | Clio pricing sensitivity study |\n| TAM at $79/mo (2–9 attorney firms) | ~$71M | 75K × $79 × 12 |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Setup Time | Price | Complexity | Small Firm Fit |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Clio Grow | 4–6 hours | $109+/user | High | Medium |\n| Lawmatics | 3–5 hours | $199–$499/mo | High | Low |\n| Intake123 | 2–3 hours | $49–$149/mo | Medium | Medium |\n| Practice Panther | 4+ hours | $49+/user | High | Low |\n| Paper/email (status quo) | 0 | $0 | Low | High |\n| **FirstContact** | < 20 min | $79/mo | Very Low | Very High |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Greg, 53, Solo Managing Partner with 2 Associates, Nashville TN**\nGreg runs a DUI and criminal defense practice. He sees 15–20 walk-in consultations per month, handles them himself, and relies on a part-time paralegal to do follow-up calls. The paralegal forgets 30–40% of follow-ups. Greg''s annual loss from missed follow-ups is estimated at $40,000–$60,000. He''s tried Clio and found it overwhelming. He wants something he can set up before his 4pm court appointment today.\n\n**Persona 2 — Amelia, 39, Partner, 4-Attorney Estate Planning Firm, Bristol UK**\nAmelia''s firm handles wills, trusts, and probate. Walk-in traffic is lower (8–12/month) but each retained client is worth £2,000–£8,000 in fees. Missing even one follow-up per month costs £2,000+. She needs consistent, professional follow-up emails that go out automatically with the firm''s letterhead branding. Her budget is £60–£70/month.\n\n**Persona 3 — Marcus, 45, Immigration Attorney, Las Vegas NV**\nMarcus runs a 3-attorney immigration firm serving Spanish-speaking clients. 60% of his walk-in consultations are in Spanish. He needs bilingual intake forms and follow-up templates (English and Spanish) to serve his client base professionally. No competitor offers native bilingual intake.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Digital Intake Form | 5 pre-built practice area templates; runs on iPad/tablet in lobby |\n| P0 | Instant Attorney Notification | SMS + email to assigned attorney within 60 seconds of form submission |\n| P0 | Automated 48hr Follow-Up | Configurable email + SMS sent 48hrs after consultation if no retainer |\n| P0 | Case Log Dashboard | Simple list: date, name, case type, attorney, status (new/contacted/retained/declined) |\n| P0 | Bilingual Support | English + Spanish forms and follow-up templates natively |\n| P1 | Conflict Check (Basic) | Name search against existing client list; simple text match |\n| P1 | Follow-Up Sequences | Up to 3 touchpoints (48hr, 1-week, 2-week); attorney can stop sequence at any time |\n| P1 | Document Capture | Photo upload at intake (ID, relevant documents via tablet camera) |\n| P1 | Source Tracking | Record how client found the firm (Google, referral, walk-in, etc.) |\n| P2 | Retainer E-Sign | Basic e-signature for retainer agreements |\n| P2 | Practice Area Analytics | Conversion rate, time-to-retainer, source attribution by practice area |\n| P2 | Clio Sync | One-way push of retained clients into Clio Manage |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Philosophy**: Simplicity and reliability over feature richness. Minimal infrastructure, maximum uptime.\n\n**Backend**: Node.js 20 + Fastify API. SQLite for firms with < 5,000 intakes; PostgreSQL as upgrade path. Deployed on Fly.io (auto-scaling, global edge).\n\n**Intake Forms**: Pure HTML forms with minimal JS; works offline (service worker caches form); submits when connection restored. Critical for firms with unreliable lobby WiFi.\n\n**Notifications**: AWS SES (email) + Twilio SMS. Notification delivery confirmed via webhook; retry 3x on failure with escalation to principal email.\n\n**Follow-Up Engine**: Simple cron-based scheduler (no workflow orchestration needed at MVP scale). PostgreSQL (or SQLite) stores follow-up queue; cron runs every 15 minutes.\n\n**Frontend**: React + TailwindCSS. Designed for 10-inch iPad in portrait mode (lobby kiosk) and 13-inch laptop (attorney dashboard).\n\n**Infrastructure**: Fly.io (API), Upstash Redis (rate limiting), Cloudflare R2 (document storage). Sub-$50/month infrastructure cost per 100 firms.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Attorneys | Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Solo | $79/mo | Up to 3 attorneys | All P0 features, 1 location |\n| Firm | $129/mo | Up to 8 attorneys | P0 + P1 features, analytics |\n| Multi-office | $199/mo | Unlimited | Everything + Clio sync, API |\n\nAdditional language packs (beyond EN + ES): $10/mo each.\n\nAt 1,200 firms: 55% Solo, 35% Firm, 10% Multi-office = $52K + $54K + $24K = $130K MRR... adjusted for actual 1,200 × blended $79.50 = $95,400 MRR = $1.14M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Intake forms (5 templates, EN+ES), attorney notification, case log dashboard |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Automated follow-up sequences, basic conflict check, document capture |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Multi-attorney firm support, source tracking, follow-up analytics |\n| M4 | Months 7–9 | Retainer e-sign, Clio sync, practice area analytics, additional language packs |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 | M6 | M20 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying firms | 80 | 350 | 1,200 |\n| MRR | $6,500 | $28,000 | $95,400 |\n| Avg. setup time (new firm) | < 25 min | < 20 min | < 15 min |\n| Follow-up delivery rate | > 96% | > 98% | > 99% |\n| Consultation-to-retainer lift | +12% | +22% | +35% |\n| Bilingual form usage | > 20% | > 25% | > 30% |\n| Monthly churn | < 5% | < 4% | < 3% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| "Too simple" perception vs. Clio | Medium | Medium | Position as "Clio-compatible front door"; market alongside Clio, not against it |\n| SQLite not suitable for multi-tenant at scale | Low | Medium | PostgreSQL migration path built from day one; SQLite for < 2,000 intakes only |\n| Bilingual compliance (Spanish legal terminology) | Medium | High | Native Spanish speaker lawyer reviews all template translations; no machine translation in legal templates |\n| Attorney adoption resistance to new workflow | High | Medium | Adoption driven by reception staff, not attorneys; attorney interaction is passive (receives notification) |\n| Fly.io outage during peak intake hours | Low | Medium | Multi-region deployment; 99.9% uptime SLA from Fly.io; status page for all clients |\n', '[{"step":"positioning","decision":"Compete on simplicity not features","reason":"Market research showed 67% of target firms willing to pay under $100/mo; all competitors above $100 add complexity; simplicity is the gap"},{"step":"bilingual","decision":"Include Spanish as native P0 feature","reason":"22% of US law firms serve Spanish-speaking populations; no competitor offers native bilingual intake; immediate differentiation in a large segment"},{"step":"infrastructure","decision":"Fly.io over AWS for initial deployment","reason":"Fly.io global edge reduces latency for multi-region from day one; simpler ops for 2-person team; $50/mo vs. $300+/mo AWS equivalent"},{"step":"offline_support","decision":"Service worker offline form submission","reason":"10% of beta firms reported lobby WiFi outages causing form failures; offline-first form is a critical reliability feature, not a nice-to-have"},{"step":"db_strategy","decision":"SQLite as default with PostgreSQL upgrade path","reason":"Most firms will have < 500 intakes/month; SQLite eliminates DB hosting cost for first 6 months and simplifies deployment while preserving upgrade path"}]',
 'submitted', 37, NOW() - INTERVAL '29 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '30 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '29 days');

INSERT INTO contributions (idea_id, author_id, content, decision_log, status, view_count, submitted_at, created_at, updated_at) VALUES

-- =============================================================
-- IDEA 9: Rural B&B Booking Manager
-- Authors: 4, 16, 25
-- =============================================================

(9, 4, E'# HarvestStay: Reservation Management for Rural B&Bs and Country Lodges\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nHarvestStay is a purpose-built reservation and operations management platform for rural bed & breakfasts, country lodges, and boutique countryside inns with 10–30 rooms. Unlike full-service hotel PMS systems designed for 100+ room properties, HarvestStay is engineered for owner-operated small lodgings where the same person takes bookings, manages housekeeping, handles cancellations, and prepares breakfast. The platform integrates direct booking (via embeddable widget or standalone page), OTA sync (Booking.com, Airbnb, Expedia), peak-season rate management, and cancellation policy enforcement into a single dashboard that requires no hospitality IT expertise to operate. Priced at $89/month. Target: 2,000 properties, $2.1M ARR by Month 30.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| B&Bs and small inns in US | ~17,000 | PAII (Professional Association of Innkeepers) 2024 |\n| B&Bs and guest houses in UK | ~25,000 | VisitBritain 2023 |\n| Average occupancy rate (rural B&B) | 58% | PAII Annual Report |\n| Average nightly rate (rural US B&B) | $142 | STR Small Lodging Report 2024 |\n| Average nightly rate (rural UK B&B) | £89 | VisitBritain Accommodation Survey |\n| OTA commission (Booking.com avg) | 15–18% | Booking.com terms 2024 |\n| Revenue lost to OTA commissions per property/yr | ~$14,200 | Based on 58% occupancy, 10 rooms, $142/night |\n| Willingness to use direct booking tool | 74% | PAII member survey 2023 |\n| TAM (US + UK properties) | ~$377M | 42K properties × $750 avg annual software spend |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Strengths | Weaknesses | Price |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Cloudbeds | Full PMS, good OTA sync | $200–$600/mo; too complex for 10-room properties | $200+/mo |\n| Little Hotelier | Purpose-built small properties | Clunky UI; slow mobile experience | $109–$199/mo |\n| Lodgify | Good booking widget | Limited channel manager; weak reporting | $12–$32/mo |\n| Beds24 | Flexible, powerful | Very steep learning curve; poor onboarding | $6–$40/mo |\n| Hostaway | Vacation rental focus | Not B&B-specific; poor breakfast/room type support | $100+/mo |\n| **HarvestStay** | Rural B&B-specific, simple, full channel sync | New entrant | $89/mo |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Carol, 58, Owner, 14-Room Country B&B, Cotswolds UK**\nCarol has operated her family farmhouse B&B for 18 years. She currently takes bookings via email and phone, manually entering them into a paper diary. She''s on Booking.com (16% commission) and loses £18,000/year in commissions she could recapture with direct bookings. She tried Cloudbeds but couldn''t navigate it. She wants something she can set up over a weekend without calling a helpline.\n\n**Persona 2 — Bill, 63, Owner, 22-Room Mountain Lodge, Asheville NC**\nBill''s lodge runs at 45% average occupancy but spikes to 95%+ on fall foliage weekends. His pain point is peak-season chaos: double bookings from taking phone and OTA reservations simultaneously, last-minute cancellations without deposit enforcement, and guests who request specific room types he can''t reliably track. He needs an inventory-locked system that prevents double bookings and enforces his 72-hour cancellation policy.\n\n**Persona 3 — Janet, 49, Owner, 11-Room Lakeside Inn, Vermont**\nJanet is digitally comfortable—she manages her own Airbnb and Booking.com profiles and uses Square for transactions. Her frustration is the lack of a unified calendar: she manually blocks dates across platforms after each booking, a process that takes 20 minutes per reservation and causes occasional double bookings. She wants automatic two-way calendar sync across all her channels.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Reservation Calendar | Visual grid showing all rooms × all dates; color-coded by booking source |\n| P0 | OTA Channel Sync | Two-way iCal + API sync with Booking.com, Airbnb, Expedia; prevents double bookings |\n| P0 | Direct Booking Widget | Embeddable booking button + availability page for owner''s website |\n| P0 | Cancellation Policy Engine | Configurable policies (24hr/48hr/72hr/non-refundable); auto-charge deposit on violation |\n| P0 | Automated Guest Emails | Booking confirmation, pre-arrival instructions, post-stay review request |\n| P1 | Peak Season Rate Rules | Set rates by season, day of week, or special event; minimum stay enforcement |\n| P1 | Stripe Payment Integration | Deposits at booking, balance before arrival, automatic card capture |\n| P1 | Room Type Management | Define room types with photos, amenities, max occupancy, base rates |\n| P1 | Housekeeping Board | Daily checkout/check-in list with room status (clean/dirty/inspected) |\n| P1 | Guest CRM | Guest history, preferences, special requests; repeat guest recognition |\n| P2 | Reporting Dashboard | Occupancy, ADR, RevPAR, revenue by source, month-over-month comparison |\n| P2 | Gift Vouchers | Sell and redeem digital gift vouchers for stays |\n| P2 | Direct Booking Incentive | Offer OTA guests a lower direct rate on checkout confirmation emails |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Channel Manager**: iCal sync (Airbnb default) + Booking.com Connectivity API (partner program) + Expedia Partner Solutions API. Update propagation < 2 minutes on booking. Optimistic lock on room-date inventory to prevent race-condition double bookings.\n\n**Backend**: Go 1.23 + Echo v4. PostgreSQL 16 with per-room-per-date inventory table. Redis for channel sync queue.\n\n**Booking Engine**: Server-rendered availability page (Next.js static generation + ISR, 60-second revalidation) for SEO and fast mobile load times. Direct booking checkout via Stripe Payment Elements.\n\n**Calendar Frontend**: React + FullCalendar Pro (hospitality-optimized resource view). Drag-to-move reservations with optimistic UI updates.\n\n**Infrastructure**: DigitalOcean App Platform + managed PostgreSQL + Spaces (for room photos). Cloudflare for CDN and DDoS protection.\n\n**Reliability**: Availability calendar served from read replica; writes go to primary. 99.9% uptime SLA target (critical during peak booking windows).\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Rooms | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Starter | $89/mo | Up to 15 rooms | Core booking, 2 OTA channels, basic rate rules |\n| Growth | $149/mo | Up to 30 rooms | All OTAs, peak rate rules, housekeeping, guest CRM |\n| Annual discount | 15% | — | 2 months free on annual commitment |\n| Booking.com direct API fee | Included | — | No per-reservation fees |\n\nAt 2,000 properties (70% Starter, 30% Growth): $124,600 + $89,400 = $214K MRR = $2.57M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–3 | Reservation calendar, room types, manual reservations, guest confirmation emails |\n| M2 | Months 4–5 | Airbnb iCal sync, Booking.com API sync, cancellation policy, Stripe deposits |\n| M3 | Months 6–7 | Direct booking widget, peak season rate rules, housekeeping board |\n| M4 | Months 8–10 | Guest CRM, reporting dashboard, Expedia sync, gift vouchers, mobile app |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M4 | M12 | M30 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying properties | 100 | 600 | 2,000 |\n| MRR | $9,500 | $65,000 | $214,000 |\n| Double booking incidents per 1K reservations | < 2 | < 0.5 | < 0.1 |\n| Direct booking share (vs. OTA) lift | +8% | +18% | +28% |\n| OTA sync lag (booking to update) | < 3 min | < 2 min | < 90 sec |\n| Annual cancellation policy violation revenue captured | $800/property | $1,400/property | $2,100/property |\n| NPS | ≥ 45 | ≥ 58 | ≥ 68 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Booking.com API connectivity approval delay | High | High | Apply for Booking.com Connectivity Partner status at founding; iCal fallback during approval period |\n| Double booking due to sync delay | Medium | Very High | Optimistic lock + inventory reservation system; 2-minute max sync window; real-time availability via webhook |\n| Rural broadband makes app slow | High | Medium | Server-rendered pages; progressive enhancement; offline-capable housekeeping board via service worker |\n| Cloudbeds drops pricing to compete | Medium | Medium | Differentiate on simplicity and onboarding speed; annual contract discount locks in churn-resistant cohort |\n| UK properties need VAT invoicing | High | Medium | UK-compliant VAT receipts at M3; MTD (Making Tax Digital) export at M4 |\n', '[{"step":"market_focus","decision":"Target 10–30 room properties specifically","reason":"Sub-10 rooms use Airbnb natively; over-30 rooms have IT budgets for Cloudbeds; 10–30 room segment is underserved by purpose-built tools"},{"step":"channel_sync","decision":"Build native Booking.com API integration in M2","reason":"iCal-only sync has 15–60 min delay; Booking.com API enables real-time inventory lock preventing double bookings; critical for trust"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$89 flat below Little Hotelier ($109+)","reason":"Price is the primary purchase objection in B&B owner interviews; $89/mo is psychologically below $100 threshold; still sustainable at 2,000 properties"},{"step":"direct_booking","decision":"Direct booking widget as P0 alongside OTA sync","reason":"OTA commission recapture is the #1 pain point; without direct booking, platform solves sync but not economics"},{"step":"architecture","decision":"Go backend for inventory locking","reason":"Go goroutines handle concurrent booking requests with channel-safe inventory locks; Node.js single-thread creates race condition risk during peak booking windows"}]',
 'submitted', 48, NOW() - INTERVAL '33 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '34 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '33 days'),

(9, 16, E'# InnSync: The Property Management Companion for Independent Rural Lodges\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nInnSync is a cloud-based property management and guest experience platform designed for independent rural lodges, country B&Bs, and farm stays in the 10–30 room segment. The platform''s distinctive approach is its "guest journey" philosophy: rather than focusing purely on reservation logistics, InnSync maps the complete guest experience from first booking inquiry through post-stay advocacy, automating touchpoints at each stage. This yields measurably higher guest satisfaction scores, more repeat bookings, and stronger review volume on TripAdvisor and Google—the organic growth engine that rural properties depend on. Built as a mobile-first PWA, InnSync is designed for owners who manage their property from their phone while walking the grounds. Priced at $109/month. Target: 1,500 properties, $1.96M ARR by Month 28.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Rural B&Bs and lodges (US + UK + Canada) | ~48,000 | PAII, VisitBritain, CBSA 2024 |\n| Average review volume per property per year | 42 new reviews | TripAdvisor SMB Hospitality Report |\n| Revenue lift from 1-star TripAdvisor improvement | +9% ADR | Cornell Hospitality Research 2023 |\n| Repeat guest rate (with active CRM) | 34% vs 18% | PAII Member Performance Data |\n| Average stay value uplift from upsells | +$38/stay | Revinate Hospitality Benchmark |\n| Properties using dedicated PMS | 41% | PAII Digital Maturity Survey 2024 |\n| Average time owner spends on booking admin/week | 11 hrs | PAII |\n| Guest experience software adoption intent | 58% | InnSync pre-launch survey, n=145 |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Guest Experience Focus | Mobile-First | Rural B&B Fit | Price |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Cloudbeds | Low | Partial | Poor (too complex) | $200+/mo |\n| Little Hotelier | Low | Partial | Medium | $109–$199/mo |\n| Guesty | None | Yes | Poor (vacation rental) | $150+/mo |\n| Lodgify | None | Partial | Medium | $12–$32/mo |\n| Revinate | High (hotel focus) | No | Poor (enterprise) | $500+/mo |\n| **InnSync** | Core differentiation | Yes (PWA) | Designed for it | $109/mo |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Dorothy, 61, Owner, 18-Room Victorian B&B, Bath UK**\nDorothy''s property has 4.7 stars on TripAdvisor with 380 reviews, largely built through her personal correspondence with guests. She currently writes thank-you notes by hand and calls guests on their anniversary of first visit. She wants technology that scales her personal touch: automated messages that feel handwritten, anniversary recognition, and proactive review requests that don''t feel impersonal. Budget: £80–£100/month.\n\n**Persona 2 — Scott, 47, Owner, 24-Room Ranch Lodge, Montana**\nScott''s hunting and fishing lodge runs 6-month seasons with near-100% occupancy in peak months. He manages everything from his phone while on the property. His frustration is losing valuable guest preference data (favorite cabin, preferred meal times, fishing skill level) between seasons—he rebuilds it from memory each year. He wants a mobile-first system that captures guest preferences automatically and surfaces them at check-in.\n\n**Persona 3 — Emily, 38, Owner, 12-Room Farm Stay, Devon UK**\nEmily opened her farm stay 2 years ago and relies entirely on Airbnb and Booking.com for visibility. She has never solicited a direct booking. She knows her OTA dependency is a vulnerability. She wants a professional direct booking page, guest communication automation, and a simple way to build a mailing list from past OTA guests for retargeting with direct booking offers.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Reservation Management | Calendar grid + list view; room types, multi-night stays, group bookings |\n| P0 | OTA Channel Sync | Two-way sync with Airbnb, Booking.com via iCal + API; real-time inventory lock |\n| P0 | Guest Journey Automation | Pre-booking inquiry response, booking confirmation, pre-arrival welcome, check-in day reminder, post-stay thank-you + review request |\n| P0 | Mobile PWA Dashboard | Full reservation management, housekeeping board, and guest messaging from mobile |\n| P0 | Stripe Payment Collection | Deposit at booking, balance collection, no-show charge enforcement |\n| P1 | Guest Preference Profiles | Auto-capture room preferences, dietary notes, special occasions, past stay history |\n| P1 | Direct Booking Page | SEO-optimized standalone page with live availability, best-rate guarantee badge |\n| P1 | Peak Rate Management | Season-based pricing rules, minimum stay requirements, early-bird discounts |\n| P1 | Review Request Engine | Timed post-stay email/SMS; one-click links to TripAdvisor, Google, Booking.com |\n| P2 | Upsell Add-Ons | Pre-arrival upsell of breakfast packages, activity bookings, room upgrades |\n| P2 | Repeat Guest Program | Recognize returning guests at booking; offer loyalty rates automatically |\n| P2 | Marketing Email Campaigns | Quarterly newsletter or seasonal offer to past guest email list |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Mobile PWA**: Next.js 14 with service worker (Workbox). Offline-capable housekeeping board and check-in list cached locally. Push notifications via Web Push API for new bookings and check-in day reminders.\n\n**Backend**: Go 1.22 + Fiber v2 REST API. PostgreSQL 15. Redis for channel sync queues and push notification queuing.\n\n**Guest Journey Engine**: State machine per reservation (inquiry → confirmed → pre-arrival → arrived → departed → reviewed). Each state transition triggers configured automation (email/SMS/webhook). Temporal.io for durable delay scheduling (send 3-day pre-arrival email exactly 72hrs before check-in).\n\n**Channel Sync**: Booking.com Connectivity API (real-time) + Airbnb iCal (5-minute polling). Inventory held in Redis with DB persistence for double-booking prevention.\n\n**Payments**: Stripe Terminal integration for in-property payments (optional card reader); Stripe Payment Links for remote deposit collection.\n\n**Infrastructure**: AWS (ECS Fargate, RDS, ElastiCache). CDN via CloudFront for direct booking pages (critical for SEO performance).\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Rooms | Highlights |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Essential | $109/mo | Up to 20 rooms | Full guest journey, OTA sync, payments |\n| Premium | $179/mo | Up to 40 rooms | + upsells, loyalty program, marketing emails |\n| Annual (Essential) | $981/yr | — | Save $327 (25% off) |\n\nAt 1,500 properties (75% Essential, 25% Premium): $122.6K + $67.1K = $189.7K MRR = $2.27M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–3 | Reservation calendar, room management, guest confirmation emails, Stripe payments, mobile PWA |\n| M2 | Months 4–6 | OTA sync (Airbnb + Booking.com), guest journey automation engine, pre-arrival messaging |\n| M3 | Months 7–8 | Guest preference profiles, review request engine, peak rate management, direct booking page |\n| M4 | Months 9–11 | Upsell add-ons, repeat guest program, marketing email campaigns, reporting dashboard |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M4 | M12 | M28 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying properties | 80 | 500 | 1,500 |\n| MRR | $8,720 | $60,000 | $189,700 |\n| Guest journey email open rate | > 55% | > 62% | > 68% |\n| Post-stay review conversion | > 18% | > 25% | > 32% |\n| Direct booking share lift | +6% | +15% | +25% |\n| Guest preference profile completeness | 45% | 62% | 78% |\n| Mobile vs. desktop usage (owner) | > 65% | > 72% | > 78% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Airbnb restricts iCal access or changes API | Medium | High | Maintain direct API partnership track; iCal is standard and legally protected use |\n| Review solicitation violates TripAdvisor/Google TOS | Medium | High | Only send review invites to opted-in guests; link to platform review pages, never offer incentives |\n| Mobile PWA performance on 3G rural connections | High | Medium | Aggressive asset optimization; offline-first for housekeeping; skeleton screens for perceived performance |\n| Owner tech resistance to new system | High | High | White-glove migration from paper/Airbnb for first 50 properties; dedicated onboarding specialist role |\n| UK/EU GDPR for guest data profiles | Medium | High | Privacy policy templates provided; consent captured at booking; data export on guest request |\n', '[{"step":"differentiation","decision":"Guest experience automation as primary value prop, not just PMS","reason":"Rural B&Bs compete on personal touch, not price; technology that amplifies personal touch is 10x more compelling than generic scheduling software"},{"step":"mobile_first","decision":"PWA over native iOS/Android app for MVP","reason":"PWA ships on one codebase; push notifications and offline support via Workbox are sufficient for owner use case; native app adds 3–4 months to MVP timeline"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$109 at Essential tier matches Little Hotelier but offers guest journey automation they lack","reason":"Side-by-side feature comparison shows InnSync delivers 2x more automation at same price; value is clear without undercutting on price"},{"step":"direct_booking","decision":"Include SEO-optimized standalone booking page, not just embeddable widget","reason":"Owners without websites (35% of target segment) need a complete direct booking presence; standalone page serves both website-owners and website-less operators"},{"step":"upsell_engine","decision":"Defer upsell add-ons to M4","reason":"Core booking + guest journey must be solid before layering upsell complexity; premature upsell features distract from primary value prop at launch"}]',
 'submitted', 56, NOW() - INTERVAL '26 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '27 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '26 days'),

(9, 25, E'# RoomRoost: Zero-Complexity Booking Manager for Countryside B&Bs\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nRoomRoost is built on a radical simplicity philosophy: the ideal booking tool for a rural 15-room B&B is one that the owner''s 70-year-old mother could navigate on an iPad without instructions. The platform deliberately excludes features that confuse non-technical users—no rate plans with 12 variables, no complex distribution matrix, no training required. What RoomRoost does instead: shows a clean room calendar, accepts online bookings, sends automatic confirmation and reminder emails, and blocks the room across Airbnb and Booking.com. Full stop. This MVP clarity enables a 10-minute setup time and a $59/month price point that is the lowest in the category with real OTA sync capability. Target: 3,000 properties at $59/month = $2.12M ARR by Month 24 via product-led growth with near-zero CAC.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| B&Bs + guest houses (US, UK, Canada, AUS combined) | ~78,000 | Aggregated national tourism boards |\n| % without dedicated PMS software | 59% | PAII 2024 |\n| % using only Airbnb / Booking.com for management | 38% | PAII |\n| Average OTA commission rate | 16.2% | Phocuswire OTA Cost Study 2024 |\n| Annual commission cost (10-room property, 65% occ.) | ~$10,700 | Own calculation |\n| Price sensitivity threshold (B&B owners) | $50–$75/mo | RoomRoost pre-launch interviews, n=68 |\n| Setup time tolerance | < 30 min | Same interview cohort |\n| Average tech proficiency score (B&B owners, 1–10) | 4.2 | Same cohort |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Setup Time | Minimum Price | OTA Sync | Simplicity Rating (1–10) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Cloudbeds | 6–8 hours | $200/mo | Yes | 3 |\n| Little Hotelier | 3–4 hours | $109/mo | Yes | 5 |\n| Beds24 | 4–6 hours | $6/mo | Yes | 2 |\n| Lodgify | 1–2 hours | $12/mo | Partial | 6 |\n| Hostaway | 2–3 hours | $100/mo | Yes | 4 |\n| **RoomRoost** | < 10 min | $59/mo | Yes (iCal + API) | 9 |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Margaret, 67, Retired Teacher turned B&B Owner, Lake District UK**\nMargaret opened her 12-room former farmhouse to guests 4 years ago. She manages bookings in a paper diary and uses Booking.com because "the nice man in the village showed me how." She has heard horror stories about double bookings from friends in her B&B network. She refuses to use anything with more options than her microwave. If RoomRoost can prevent double bookings and send a confirmation email automatically, it''s worth £45/month.\n\n**Persona 2 — Chuck, 59, Former Construction Foreman, B&B Owner, Smoky Mountains TN**\nChuck opened a 20-room mountain lodge 3 years ago. He''s on Airbnb, Booking.com, and VRBO simultaneously and manually blocks dates across all three after each booking—a 15-minute exercise he''s done 400+ times. He has had 3 double bookings in two years and it nearly cost him his Airbnb superhost status. He wants automatic blocking, nothing else. Budget: $60–$80/month.\n\n**Persona 3 — Niamh, 44, Owner, 16-Room Coastal B&B, County Clare IE**\nNiamh''s property is fully booked 5 months of the year via Booking.com but she has no direct booking capability. She wants to reduce Booking.com dependency and capture direct bookings, but she won''t use anything that requires a tutorial. She needs a booking link she can share on Instagram, Facebook, and WhatsApp that shows live availability.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Room Calendar | One-screen view: rooms as rows, dates as columns, bookings as colored blocks |\n| P0 | iCal OTA Sync | Automatic two-way iCal sync with Airbnb, Booking.com, VRBO; updates within 5 minutes |\n| P0 | Direct Booking Link | Shareable URL showing live availability; complete booking in < 3 minutes |\n| P0 | Booking Confirmation Email | Auto-sent on booking; includes property directions, arrival instructions |\n| P0 | Cancellation Block | 48hr/72hr cancellation policy with auto-notification to guest |\n| P1 | Stripe Deposit | Optional deposit at booking; auto-captured on arrival date if balance outstanding |\n| P1 | Pre-Arrival Reminder | SMS + email 3 days before check-in; customizable text |\n| P1 | Booking.com API Sync | Upgrade from iCal to real-time API for properties needing < 5-min sync |\n| P1 | Room Photo Gallery | Upload 5 photos per room type; shown on direct booking page |\n| P2 | Simple Reporting | Monthly occupancy %, revenue summary, bookings by source |\n| P2 | Guest Notes | One free-text field per guest record for owner notes |\n| P2 | Multi-Property | Same login for owners with 2–3 properties |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Radical Simplicity Principle**: Every feature must pass the "can Margaret use it" test. No feature is shipped if it requires a tooltip to explain.\n\n**Backend**: Rails 7.2 API mode. PostgreSQL. Sidekiq + Redis for OTA sync jobs and email dispatch.\n\n**iCal Engine**: Custom iCal parser and generator (RFC 5545 compliant). Polling loop runs every 5 minutes per connected calendar. Detected new VEVENT blocks trigger local reservation creation and availability lock.\n\n**Direct Booking**: Statically rendered availability page (Hotwire Turbo Frames for real-time slot updates without full page reload). No JS framework—vanilla JS only for calendar slot selection.\n\n**Email**: Postmark for high deliverability. Plain-text emails with minimal formatting—designed to look like a personal note from the owner.\n\n**Payments**: Stripe Payment Links (hosted checkout)—no PCI scope on RoomRoost infrastructure.\n\n**Infrastructure**: Render.com (Rails + Sidekiq). Render PostgreSQL. Cloudflare for DNS + DDoS.\n\n**Onboarding UX**: 4-step wizard (add rooms → connect OTAs → set cancellation policy → copy booking link). Completion rate target: > 85% within 15 minutes.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Rooms | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Solo | $59/mo | Up to 20 rooms | All features; single property |\n| Multi | $89/mo | Up to 60 rooms (3 properties) | For owners with 2–3 lodges |\n| Annual | $531/yr (Solo) | — | 25% discount; 2 months free |\n\nAt 3,000 properties (90% Solo, 10% Multi): $159,300 + $26,700 = $186,000 MRR = $2.23M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Room calendar, iCal OTA sync (Airbnb + Booking.com + VRBO), booking confirmation email |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Direct booking link + page, cancellation policy, pre-arrival SMS/email reminder |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Stripe deposit, room photos, Booking.com API upgrade, basic reporting |\n| M4 | Months 7–8 | Guest notes, multi-property support, mobile app (React Native, read-only calendar + notifications) |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M2 | M6 | M24 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Registered properties | 200 | 800 | 4,000 |\n| Paying properties | 50 | 400 | 3,000 |\n| Onboarding completion rate (< 15 min) | > 70% | > 80% | > 88% |\n| Double booking incidents | < 1% of reservations | < 0.3% | < 0.1% |\n| MRR | $3,200 | $27,000 | $186,000 |\n| NPS | ≥ 55 | ≥ 65 | ≥ 72 |\n| Monthly churn | < 4% | < 3% | < 2% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| iCal sync 5-min delay still causes double bookings | Medium | High | Display sync lag warning to owners; recommend Booking.com API upgrade for high-volume properties |\n| "Too simple" perceived as unprofessional by some | Low | Low | Target market explicitly wants simple; NPS will validate; add complexity only if churn data demands it |\n| Render.com outage during peak booking period (UK summer) | Low | High | Multi-region Render deployment; status page; manual booking fallback email instructions |\n| Competing on price drives race to bottom | Medium | Medium | Compete on simplicity NPS, not price; annual plan locks in churn-resistant cohort |\n| GDPR for EU/UK guest data | Medium | High | Privacy policy template provided at onboarding; data processing agreement for EU properties; Cloudflare data residency in EU |\n', '[{"step":"core_philosophy","decision":"Radical simplicity as the product strategy","reason":"Market interview with 68 B&B owners showed average tech proficiency of 4.2/10; every competitor underserves this cohort by adding features; simplicity IS the moat"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$59 below $89 competitors","reason":"Price sensitivity interviews showed $50–$75 threshold; $59 is comfortably within range and undercuts Little Hotelier by 46%"},{"step":"ota_sync","decision":"iCal first, Booking.com API as P1 upgrade","reason":"iCal requires no partner approval; ships faster; 5-min sync acceptable for most properties; API upgrade offered as self-serve option for high-volume operators"},{"step":"email_style","decision":"Plain-text confirmation emails over HTML templates","reason":"Plain-text emails have 22% higher open rates; feel like personal messages; matches rural B&B brand identity; lower spam score"},{"step":"tech_stack","decision":"Rails + Hotwire over Next.js SPA","reason":"Hotwire delivers interactive UI without complex JS; server-rendered pages are fast on rural 4G; Rails productivity advantage critical for 2-person team at early stage"}]',
 'submitted', 40, NOW() - INTERVAL '18 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '19 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '18 days'),

