(10, 6, E'# ShowingIQ: Client Intelligence and Follow-Up Platform for Residential Agents\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nShowingIQ is a showing management and buyer intelligence platform for residential real estate agents handling 20–50 property showings per month. The platform addresses the critical gap between a showing and a closed transaction: agents typically lose track of buyer feedback after showings, fail to follow up with undecided clients at optimal intervals, and have no analytical view of what property attributes actually correlate with offers. ShowingIQ captures structured feedback immediately after each showing via a 60-second mobile form, tracks each buyer''s preference evolution over time, automates follow-up sequences based on engagement signals, and surfaces conversion pattern analytics to help agents identify which showings are most likely to close. Priced at $49/month per agent. Target: 5,000 agents, $2.94M ARR by Month 30.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| Licensed residential real estate agents (US) | ~1.6M | NAR 2024 |\n| Active agents (6+ transactions/yr) | ~420,000 | NAR |\n| Agents with 20+ showings/month | ~85,000 | Estimated top 20% by activity |\n| Average showings per closed transaction | 8.7 | NAR Buyer Survey 2024 |\n| Average gross commission per closed sale | $9,200 | NAR (median home $412K × 2.3% buy-side) |\n| Deals lost to poor follow-up per agent per year | 3–5 | Agent interview estimate, n=42 |\n| Annual revenue impact of improved follow-up | $27,600–$46,000 | 3–5 deals × $9,200 |\n| Real estate tech software spend per agent per year | $1,420 | T3 Sixty Real Estate Technology Report 2024 |\n| SAM (US agents, 20+ showings/mo) | ~$50M | 85K agents × $49 × 12 |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Showing Tracking | Buyer Intelligence | Follow-Up Automation | Price |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Follow Up Boss | No | Basic CRM | Yes (generic) | $69–$500+/mo |\n| BoomTown | No | Lead focused | Yes | $1,000+/mo |\n| LionDesk | No | Basic | Limited | $25–$49/mo |\n| ShowingTime | Scheduling only | None | None | $35–$60/mo |\n| Propertybase | Basic | Partial | Limited | $79+/mo/user |\n| **ShowingIQ** | Core feature | Preference tracking | Behavior-triggered | $49/mo |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Jennifer, 38, Residential Buyer''s Agent, Austin TX**\nJennifer handles 35–45 showings per month across a hot market. After each showing, she texts brief notes to herself in an unstructured format that she rarely reviews. She has lost 2 buyers this year to competing agents who were more responsive. She wants a system that prompts her for structured feedback at the showing and sends intelligent follow-up messages based on buyer interest level—without her having to remember who to call.\n\n**Persona 2 — Kevin, 51, Team Lead, 4-Agent Buyer''s Team, Denver CO**\nKevin manages a team of 4 buyer''s agents each running 20–30 showings per month. His challenge is visibility: he cannot see which buyers are hot and which have gone cold across his team''s activities. He needs a team dashboard showing all showings, feedback scores, follow-up status, and conversion probability across all agents. He currently gets this information from a weekly team call that misses nuance.\n\n**Persona 3 — Diane, 45, Independent Agent, Richmond VA**\nDiane works solo with a focus on repeat and referral business. She shows 20–25 properties per month to 8–12 active buyers. Her problem is analysis: after 6 months of showings with a client, she has no data on their actual preference patterns—only memory and scattered notes in her iPhone. ShowingIQ''s preference evolution tracking would help her proactively identify when a buyer is ready to make an offer.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Post-Showing Feedback Form | 60-second mobile form (star ratings + free text) captured at or immediately after showing |\n| P0 | Buyer Preference Tracker | Aggregates feedback across all showings per buyer; identifies evolving preference patterns |\n| P0 | Follow-Up Reminder Engine | Behavior-triggered reminders: 24hr after showing, 3-day if no response, 7-day for warm leads |\n| P0 | Showing Log | Chronological record per buyer: property, date, agent notes, feedback score, next action |\n| P0 | Conversion Pipeline | Kanban view: Active Searching → Offers Made → Under Contract → Closed |\n| P1 | Team Dashboard | Manager view across all agents: showing volume, feedback rates, pipeline by agent |\n| P1 | Property Match Score | Scores new listings against buyer''s preference profile; alerts agent when strong match appears |\n| P1 | Automated Follow-Up Sequences | Pre-built email + SMS sequences by buyer stage (early, warm, hot, post-offer) |\n| P1 | MLS Integration | Import listing data (address, price, beds/baths) into showing log from MLS RETS/IDX |\n| P2 | Conversion Analytics | Which property attributes (price range, neighborhood, age) correlate with offers for this agent |\n| P2 | Buyer Presentation Mode | Share curated showing history with buyer as a visual journey toward their ideal home |\n| P2 | Referral Tracking | Link closed transactions to source; identify top referral channels |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Backend**: Go 1.23 + Echo v4 REST API. PostgreSQL 16. Redis for session state and async job queue.\n\n**Mobile Form UX**: Progressive Web App optimized for one-handed phone use (large tap targets, minimal typing, star ratings + optional free text). Works offline; syncs when connection restored—critical for rural showings.\n\n**Preference Analytics Engine**: Per-buyer preference vector built from aggregated showing feedback. Attributes tracked: price range satisfaction, neighborhood, square footage, condition, commute tolerance, yard/outdoor space. Updated incrementally. New listing match score = cosine similarity between listing attributes and preference vector.\n\n**Follow-Up Engine**: Temporal.io durable workflows. Workflows triggered on showing log creation; follow-up schedule adapts based on buyer''s reply signal (opened email → wait 3 days; no open → escalate to SMS).\n\n**MLS Integration**: RETS/IDX data pull via Spark API (national MLS aggregator). Address lookup auto-populates listing data into showing log on showing creation.\n\n**Frontend**: Next.js 14 App Router + TailwindCSS. Kanban pipeline built with @dnd-kit. Responsive for tablet use at open houses.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Agents | Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Solo | $49/mo | 1 agent | Full feature set for individual |\n| Team | $129/mo | Up to 5 agents | + team dashboard, manager analytics |\n| Brokerage | $299/mo | Up to 20 agents | + conversion analytics, referral tracking, API |\n| Annual discount | 20% | — | 2.5 months free |\n\nAt 5,000 agents (3,500 Solo, 1,200 Team accounts = 6,000 agents, 300 Brokerage): $171.5K + $154.8K + $89.7K = $416K MRR = $4.99M ARR... conservative: 5,000 Solo agents = $245K MRR = $2.94M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Showing log, post-showing feedback form, buyer preference tracker, basic follow-up reminders |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Conversion pipeline, automated follow-up sequences, mobile PWA optimization |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Team dashboard, property match score, MLS integration via Spark API |\n| M4 | Months 7–10 | Conversion analytics, buyer presentation mode, brokerage plan, referral tracking |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M4 | M12 | M30 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying agents | 200 | 1,500 | 5,000 |\n| MRR | $10,500 | $82,500 | $245,000 |\n| Post-showing feedback capture rate | > 65% | > 75% | > 82% |\n| Follow-up task completion rate | > 78% | > 85% | > 90% |\n| Deals attributed to ShowingIQ follow-up | 0.8/agent/mo | 1.5/agent/mo | 2.2/agent/mo |\n| Preference profile completeness (5+ showings) | > 70% | > 80% | > 88% |\n| NPS | ≥ 48 | ≥ 60 | ≥ 70 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Agents don''t capture feedback consistently | High | High | 60-second form maximum; push notification triggered 30 min after scheduled showing end; gamification badge for 30-day streak |\n| MLS access restricted by local MLS boards | High | Medium | Spark API aggregates 95% of US MLS data; fallback to manual address entry; MLS integration is P1, not P0 |\n| ShowingTime launches buyer intelligence features | Medium | High | ShowingTime is scheduling-focused; pivot to intelligence is a major product shift; accelerate preference tracking moat |\n| Real estate market downturn reduces showing volume | Medium | High | Diversify into commercial showings; add rental market use case; agent retention programs |\n| NAR settlement changes buyer agent commission | High | Medium | ShowingIQ''s ROI story becomes more important, not less; agents must prove their value — our analytics help |\n', '[{"step":"market_timing","decision":"Launch now despite NAR commission changes","reason":"Commission structure changes (NAR settlement 2024) increase pressure on buyer agents to demonstrate value — ShowingIQ''s analytics directly address this need"},{"step":"feedback_form","decision":"60-second maximum form with forced brevity","reason":"Agent interviews showed that longer forms are abandoned; structured 60-second capture beats comprehensive forms that are never completed"},{"step":"follow_up_engine","decision":"Temporal.io for durable follow-up workflows over cron","reason":"Cron-based follow-up loses state on server restart; Temporal persists workflow state durably; critical for follow-up credibility with agents"},{"step":"mls_integration","decision":"Spark API over direct MLS RETS connections","reason":"Individual MLS RETS connections require per-MLS agreements (500+ MLSs in US); Spark aggregates nationally with one API key"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$49 Solo tier, not freemium","reason":"Real estate agents are high-income professionals; freemium attracts non-serious users; $49 is < 0.6% of one commission and self-selects motivated users"}]',
 'submitted', 62, NOW() - INTERVAL '24 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '25 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '24 days'),

(10, 18, E'# TrailLog: Property Showing CRM for Independent Real Estate Agents\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nTrailLog is a lightweight, mobile-first showing and client management tool for independent residential agents who are frustrated with bloated CRM systems that cost $500+/month and require full-time admins to maintain. The platform''s core thesis is that agents need three workflow tools, not a hundred: (1) a fast way to log showing feedback while standing in a kitchen, (2) a smart follow-up reminder that triggers at the right moment based on buyer signal, and (3) a simple view of which buyers are hot and which have gone cold. TrailLog delivers exactly these three with a 10-minute onboarding and a $29/month price point designed to be a no-brainer expense on any agent''s P&L. Target: 8,000 agents, $2.78M ARR by Month 24 via word-of-mouth in agent communities.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| US licensed agents | ~1.6M | NAR 2024 |\n| % dissatisfied with current CRM | 54% | Inman Agent Survey 2024 |\n| % paying over $100/mo for RE tech | 38% | T3 Sixty 2024 |\n| Median gross commission income (active agents) | $56,000 | NAR Income Survey 2024 |\n| Software budget as % of GCI | 2.5% | T3 Sixty benchmark |\n| Agents who "would switch" for simpler tool at $30 | 41% | Inman survey |\n| Target segment (20–50 showings/mo) | ~85,000 agents | Estimated from NAR transaction data |\n| SAM at $29/mo | ~$29.6M | 85K × $29 × 12 |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Monthly Price | Showing-Specific | Mobile UX | Setup Time |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Follow Up Boss | $69–$500+ | No | Good | 3–4 hours |\n| LionDesk | $25–$49 | No | Average | 2–3 hours |\n| ShowingTime | $35–$60 | Scheduling only | Good | 1 hour |\n| Wise Agent | $49 | No | Poor | 2–3 hours |\n| Streak (Gmail CRM) | $15–$49 | No | Poor | 1–2 hours |\n| **TrailLog** | $29 | Yes | Excellent | < 10 min |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Ashley, 32, Buyer''s Agent, Phoenix AZ**\nAshley is 3 years into her real estate career and handles 25–35 showings per month. She tried Follow Up Boss on her team lead''s recommendation but cancelled after 2 months—too complex, too expensive. She currently tracks buyers in a Notes app and follows up based on memory. She has lost 2 buyers this year who "just went with another agent" after she failed to follow up at the right moment. She wants a $30 tool that replaces her Notes app.\n\n**Persona 2 — Richard, 55, Independent Agent, Edinburgh UK**\nRichard handles 20–28 showings per month in a mid-range residential market (£250K–£450K properties). He uses a paper diary and sends follow-up emails manually 2–3 days after each showing. He knows he loses clients in the gap between showings when buyers cool off without contact. He is skeptical of software but willing to try anything under £25/month that doesn''t require a course to learn.\n\n**Persona 3 — Tara, 41, RE/MAX Agent, Toronto ON**\nTara operates in Toronto''s fast-moving condo market with 40–50 showings per month. Speed of follow-up is critical—condos list and sell in 48–72 hours. She needs instant showing log capture and same-day automated follow-up triggered the moment a showing ends. Her current workflow adds 3 hours of admin per week that she''d rather spend prospecting.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Quick Log Form | Voice-to-text or tap-to-rate showing feedback in < 60 seconds from mobile |\n| P0 | Buyer Heat Score | 1–5 score updated after each showing; highlights "hot" buyers needing same-day contact |\n| P0 | Smart Follow-Up Prompts | Context-aware reminders: "Ashley hasn''t heard from you in 3 days and showed strong interest in Oak St" |\n| P0 | Showing Timeline | Per-buyer visual timeline of all properties viewed, scores, and notes |\n| P0 | Hot List Dashboard | Single view: all buyers sorted by Heat Score + last contact date |\n| P1 | Automated Follow-Up Messages | Pre-written templates for post-showing, check-in, market update, and offer readiness |\n| P1 | Property Comparison | Side-by-side view of 2–3 properties a buyer has seen; share with buyer via link |\n| P1 | Client Portal | Read-only view for buyers to review their showing history and agent notes |\n| P1 | Preference Tags | Tag showings with attributes (good school district, large yard, modern kitchen); auto-surfaces in match alerts |\n| P2 | Market Activity Alerts | Notify agent when a previously shown property drops in price or goes back on market |\n| P2 | Team Mode | Share buyers across 2–5 agent team; team leader visibility into all activities |\n| P2 | Conversion Reporting | Showings → offers → close funnel with agent-level benchmarks |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Voice-to-Text Input**: Web Speech API (native browser, no third-party cost) for feedback capture while driving. Fallback: pre-populated star rating fields. Transcribed text processed by GPT-4o-mini to extract structured tags (property attributes, buyer sentiment, price objections).\n\n**Heat Score Algorithm**: Weighted composite: feedback star rating (40%) + days since last contact (30%) + number of return viewings (20%) + response time to agent messages (10%). Recalculated nightly.\n\n**Backend**: Node.js 20 + Hono (ultra-lightweight framework). Turso (SQLite edge DB, libsql) for per-agent data isolation. Cloudflare Workers for API — sub-50ms response times globally.\n\n**Frontend**: SvelteKit (smaller bundle than React, faster initial load on mobile). TailwindCSS. Designed for one-handed mobile use.\n\n**Push Notifications**: Web Push API via Cloudflare Workers. Follow-up prompts pushed to agent''s mobile as browser notifications or iOS/Android PWA notifications.\n\n**Infrastructure**: 100% Cloudflare stack (Workers, R2, D1 or Turso). Monthly cost < $40 for 1,000 users. Linear cost scaling.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Users | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Agent | $29/mo | 1 agent | Full feature set |\n| Team | $89/mo | Up to 5 agents | + team visibility, shared buyers |\n| Annual Agent | $261/yr | 1 agent | Save $87 (25% off) |\n\nAt 8,000 Solo agents + 800 Team accounts: $232K + $71.2K = $303.2K MRR = $3.64M ARR. Conservative (70% penetration): $2.55M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–2 | Quick log form (voice + tap), buyer timeline, heat score, hot list dashboard |\n| M2 | Months 3–4 | Smart follow-up prompts, automated message templates, preference tags |\n| M3 | Months 5–6 | Property comparison view, client portal, market activity alerts |\n| M4 | Months 7–9 | Team mode, conversion reporting, iOS/Android app (React Native shell over PWA) |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M3 | M6 | M24 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Registered agents | 1,000 | 3,500 | 12,000 |\n| Paying agents | 250 | 1,800 | 8,000 |\n| MRR | $7,500 | $54,000 | $232,000 |\n| Avg. log time per showing | < 75 sec | < 60 sec | < 45 sec |\n| Follow-up prompt act-through rate | > 55% | > 65% | > 72% |\n| Heat score accuracy (agent-rated 1–5) | 3.8 | 4.2 | 4.6 |\n| Free-to-paid conversion | 18% | 22% | 28% |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Web Speech API unreliable on Android Chrome | Medium | Medium | Star-rating fallback always available; voice is enhancement not requirement |\n| Turso/SQLite edge DB read consistency issues | Low | Medium | D1 (Cloudflare native) as fallback; per-agent isolation means no cross-tenant consistency risk |\n| Follow Up Boss launches $29 tier | Low | Medium | Our moat is simplicity and showing-specific design — matching price without product redesign does not close the gap |\n| Agent adoption bottleneck at log capture habit | High | High | Gamification: showing streak badges + weekly performance digest email motivates daily usage |\n| NAR commission changes reduce buyer agent use | Medium | High | Pivot messaging: "Prove your value to clients with data-driven showing reports" — converts headwind into tailwind |\n', '[{"step":"tech_stack","decision":"Cloudflare Workers + Turso over traditional server backend","reason":"100% edge deployment eliminates server ops; sub-50ms global response critical for mobile UX; linear cost scaling allows $29 price point to be profitable from day one"},{"step":"voice_input","decision":"Web Speech API over third-party STT service","reason":"Web Speech API is free and native to Chrome/Edge/Safari; at 8,000 agents × 30 logs/month = 2.4M voice inputs, third-party cost would be $4,800+/month"},{"step":"frontend","decision":"SvelteKit over React","reason":"Svelte produces 40% smaller bundle than React equivalent; critical for fast load on 4G in rural showings; agent productivity depends on app loading instantly"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"$29 as anchor price, not freemium","reason":"$29 is below psychological resistance for active agents; freemium in B2B real estate tools attracts inactive agents who never convert; paid-from-day-one selects motivated users"},{"step":"heat_score","decision":"Composite algorithm over simple star rating","reason":"Single star rating loses signal over time; composite score incorporates recency (last contact) and behavioral signals that are stronger predictors of deal readiness"}]',
 'submitted', 58, NOW() - INTERVAL '21 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '22 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '21 days'),

(10, 26, E'# ListingLoop: Post-Showing Analytics and Buyer Conversion Intelligence for Real Estate Teams\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nListingLoop is an enterprise-light showing analytics and buyer conversion optimization platform designed for productive real estate agent teams (3–15 agents) handling a combined 60–200 showings per month. Where individual-agent tools stop at logging feedback and sending reminders, ListingLoop adds a conversion intelligence layer: statistical analysis of which property attributes, price ranges, neighborhoods, and showing sequences consistently lead to offers versus stalls. Team leaders use these insights to coach agents, adjust buyer expectations early, and allocate their time to the buyers most likely to close. The platform''s differentiated ROI story—"one additional close per agent per quarter pays for 6 months of subscription"—targets team leaders who buy software for their entire team. Priced at $199/month per team (up to 5 agents). Target: 1,500 teams, $3.58M ARR by Month 30.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source |\n|---|---|---|\n| US real estate agent teams (3+ members) | ~42,000 | NAR Team Survey 2024 |\n| Average team GCI | $284,000/yr | NAR |\n| Average closed transactions per team/yr | 31 | NAR |\n| Showings per transaction | 8.7 | NAR Buyer Survey |\n| Total showings per team per year | ~270 | 31 × 8.7 |\n| % of teams with dedicated showing analytics | < 5% | Estimated (no dedicated product exists) |\n| Revenue from one incremental closed transaction | $9,200 | NAR median GCI per transaction |\n| Annual software spend per team | ~$3,800 | T3 Sixty Team Technology Report |\n| SAM (US RE teams) | ~$160M | 42K teams × $3,800 avg spend |\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Competitor | Team Analytics | Showing-Specific | Buyer Intelligence | Price |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| BoomTown | Yes (lead gen focus) | No | Lead scoring | $1,000+/mo |\n| Follow Up Boss | Basic team view | No | Pipeline only | $500+/mo/team |\n| Sierra Interactive | Yes | No | Lead + CRM | $500–$1,500/mo |\n| kvCORE | Yes | No | Lead + CRM | $500+/mo |\n| ShowingTime | Scheduling only | Yes (scheduling) | None | $35–$60/mo |\n| **ListingLoop** | Showing analytics | Yes | Buyer preference + conversion | $199/mo/team |\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n**Persona 1 — Brandon, 44, Team Leader, 6-Agent Buyer''s Team, Orlando FL**\nBrandon''s team closes 42 transactions/year. He attends weekly pipeline reviews but has no data on why certain buyers stall after 8–10 showings—agents say "they''re picky" but Brandon suspects it''s a price expectation problem that could be resolved earlier. He wants showing analytics that surface patterns: "buyers who view 10+ properties in the $350K–$400K range and don''t offer tend to actually qualify at $320K—recommend price recalibration conversation after showing 5."\n\n**Persona 2 — Sandra, 51, Brokerage Owner, 12-Agent Mixed Residential Team, Charlotte NC**\nSandra''s brokerage handles both buyers and sellers. She wants visibility into all agent showing activities, not just pipeline status. Her goal is coaching: identifying which agents need help with follow-up (low contact rates) versus buyer qualification (high showing-to-offer ratio). ListingLoop''s agent performance dashboard gives her coaching conversations grounded in data rather than gut feel.\n\n**Persona 3 — Tim, 38, Team Lead, 4-Agent New Construction Specialist Team, Houston TX**\nTim''s team focuses exclusively on new construction communities. Buyers visit model homes multiple times before committing. His showing sequence is longer (12–18 visits on average) and tracking preference evolution across multiple community visits is complex. He needs a tool that treats each new construction visit as a data point in a longer decision journey, not a one-time showing.\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| P0 | Team Showing Dashboard | All agents'' showings in one view: date, property, buyer, feedback score, next action, days since last contact |\n| P0 | Structured Feedback Capture | Mobile form: star ratings on 6 dimensions (price, location, size, condition, schools, layout) + free text |\n| P0 | Buyer Conversion Pipeline | Kanban: Searching → Offer Ready → Under Contract → Closed; drag to move, visible to team leader |\n| P0 | Follow-Up Accountability | Team leader sees which agents have overdue follow-ups; automated escalation alerts |\n| P0 | Agent Performance Metrics | Per-agent: showings/week, feedback capture rate, avg days to offer, contact frequency |\n| P1 | Conversion Pattern Analytics | Aggregate analysis: which price ranges, neighborhoods, property types convert fastest in this team''s market |\n| P1 | Buyer Readiness Score | ML-scored probability of offer within 30 days based on feedback trajectory and engagement patterns |\n| P1 | Coaching Insights | Weekly digest for team leader: "3 buyers overdue for contact; agent Kevin''s feedback capture dropped to 58%" |\n| P1 | Property Match Alerts | New listing matches buyer preference profile; alert agent with one-click scheduling |\n| P2 | CRM Integration | Sync to Follow Up Boss, Salesforce, KVCore via API/Zapier |\n| P2 | ROI Dashboard | Revenue attributed to ListingLoop follow-ups; cost-per-closed-transaction |\n| P2 | White-Label for Brokerages | Custom branding for multi-team brokerages; 20+ agents |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n**Analytics Engine**: Python 3.12 + pandas for offline analytics batch jobs (nightly). PostgreSQL as analytical store with materialized views for agent performance metrics. On-demand queries for team leader dashboard served via pre-computed aggregates (< 200ms response time).\n\n**Readiness Score Model**: Gradient boosting (XGBoost) trained on 3,000+ historical buyer journeys from beta firms. Features: feedback score trajectory, showing frequency, days between showings, price range stability, number of return visits, response time to agent messages. Re-trained monthly as user base grows.\n\n**Backend**: Go 1.23 + Echo v4 REST API for real-time operations. Python FastAPI microservice for analytics batch triggers and model inference.\n\n**Mobile App**: React Native (iOS + Android). Offline feedback capture with local SQLite; syncs on connection restore. Critical for agents in dead zones during rural showings.\n\n**Frontend**: Next.js 14 + TailwindCSS for team leader dashboard. Data visualization via Recharts.\n\n**Infrastructure**: AWS (ECS Fargate for Go API + Python analytics, RDS PostgreSQL, S3). Terraform IaC. Target SOC 2 Type II at 18 months for brokerage enterprise sales.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price | Agents | Key Features |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Team | $199/mo | Up to 5 agents | Full platform, analytics, coaching insights |\n| Studio | $349/mo | Up to 12 agents | + white-label option, CRM integrations, ROI dashboard |\n| Brokerage | $599/mo | Up to 30 agents | + multi-team view, custom analytics, priority support |\n| Annual discount | 20% | — | 2.5 months free |\n\nAt 1,500 teams (65% Team, 25% Studio, 10% Brokerage): $194K + $130.9K + $89.9K = $414.8K MRR = $4.97M ARR. Conservative 75%: $3.73M ARR.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeline | Deliverables |\n|---|---|---|\n| M1 | Months 1–3 | Team showing dashboard, feedback capture (mobile), buyer pipeline, agent performance metrics |\n| M2 | Months 4–5 | Follow-up accountability, coaching digest emails, property match alerts |\n| M3 | Months 6–7 | Conversion pattern analytics, buyer readiness score v1, native iOS app |\n| M4 | Months 8–10 | CRM integrations, ROI dashboard, Android app, brokerage white-label, enterprise sales motion |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | M4 | M12 | M30 |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Paying teams | 80 | 500 | 1,500 |\n| MRR | $17,200 | $113,000 | $414,800 |\n| Feedback capture rate per showing | > 70% | > 80% | > 88% |\n| Buyer readiness score accuracy (AUC) | 0.72 | 0.80 | 0.86 |\n| Team leader weekly active usage | > 60% | > 72% | > 80% |\n| Agent follow-up compliance lift | +20% | +35% | +45% |\n| Incremental closes attributed per team per quarter | 0.8 | 1.5 | 2.4 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Likelihood | Impact | Mitigation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Team leaders don''t enforce agent adoption | High | High | Platform sends team leader weekly compliance digest; peer pressure and visibility drive adoption |\n| ML readiness score not accurate at low data volumes | High | Medium | Show score only after 5+ showings per buyer; confidence interval displayed; "more data needed" placeholder |\n| BoomTown/kvCORE adds showing analytics | Medium | High | Accelerate conversion analytics moat; enterprise CRM pivot would take 12–18 months for them |\n| Real estate market downturn reduces team sizes | Medium | High | Flexible downgrade to solo plan; price per agent not per team as fallback |\n| CCPA + state privacy laws for buyer data | Medium | High | Privacy policy review by real estate attorney; opt-in consent at buyer first showing; data retention limits |\n', '[{"step":"target_segment","decision":"Target teams over individual agents","reason":"Team leaders make buying decisions for 5–12 agents; $199/team is $33–$40 per agent — comparable to solo tools but larger contract value and lower churn"},{"step":"analytics_approach","decision":"Python analytics microservice alongside Go API","reason":"Go handles high-throughput real-time API; Python pandas + XGBoost is best-in-class for batch analytics; hybrid architecture plays to each language''s strength"},{"step":"readiness_score","decision":"Only display score after 5+ showings with confidence indicator","reason":"Premature scores with insufficient data erode trust; transparency about model confidence is a feature, not a bug, in an enterprise sale"},{"step":"mobile","decision":"React Native native app over PWA","reason":"Real estate agents need reliable offline capture during showings in dead zones; PWA push notifications are unreliable on iOS; native app is required for agent adoption"},{"step":"pricing","decision":"Team-based pricing at $199, not per-agent","reason":"Per-agent pricing creates friction and resistance (team leaders negotiate down); flat team price removes negotiation and enables fast close in SMB sales"}]',
 'submitted', 65, NOW() - INTERVAL '16 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '17 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '16 days');

