(17, 12, E'# VowBoard - Client-Facing Progress Hub for Wedding Planners\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nVowBoard is a client communication and progress-tracking tool that solves the most expensive problem in wedding planning: the endless "where are we?" messages from couples. Independent wedding planners spend an estimated 6-8 hours per wedding on status updates alone. VowBoard gives every couple a beautiful, always-current wedding progress hub that the planner controls — reducing inbound questions by 70% while making the planner look more organized and premium.\n\n**Core Insight**: The wedding planning software market has built tools for planners to work with, but almost nothing that makes the client experience feel polished. VowBoard starts from the couple''s perspective and works backward.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Source/Basis |\n|--------|-------|-------------|\n| US weddings/year | 2.0M | The Knot 2023 |\n| Weddings using professional planner | ~540,000 | 27% |\n| Independent planners (target) | ~45,000 | WIPA |\n| Avg inbound client messages per wedding | 85-120 | Planner interviews |\n| % messages that are status questions | ~45% | Estimate |\n| Hours lost per wedding to status comms | 6-8 hrs | User research |\n| Planner hourly billing rate (implied) | $45-$90/hr | Fee ÷ hours |\n| Cost of status comms per wedding | $270-$720 | Hours × rate |\n| Total industry cost of status overhead | $145M-$390M/yr | 540k weddings × avg cost |\n\n**The business case for planners is clear**: At $79/month, if VowBoard saves a planner 4 hours per wedding, it pays for itself on the first wedding of the month.\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Tool | Primary Use Case | Client Portal? | Mobile? | Price/mo |\n|------|-----------------|----------------|---------|----------|\n| Aisle Planner | Planner workflow suite | Limited | Poor | $49-$99 |\n| Honeybook | CRM + contracts | Partial | Good | $16-$66 |\n| Planning Pod | Venue/event management | Yes (venue-focused) | Fair | $49-$199 |\n| Dubsado | Service business CRM | Portal (generic) | Fair | $20-$40 |\n| Zola | Consumer wedding planning | Consumer-facing | Good | Free |\n| **VowBoard** | **Client progress hub** | **Yes (core product)** | **Excellent** | **$39-$79** |\n\n**Differentiation**: VowBoard is the only tool where the client experience is the primary product, not a secondary feature.\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n### Persona A: Rachel - The "Client Experience First" Planner\n- **Age**: 33, female, Nashville TN\n- **Weddings/year**: 20, full-service, avg $6,000 fee\n- **Brand positioning**: "Luxury experience for non-luxury budgets"\n- **Current problem**: Her process is excellent but her client-facing tools look amateurish compared to her boutique brand\n- **Dream scenario**: Client opens a link and sees a beautiful, branded progress hub that makes Rachel look like a $10k planner\n- **Specific annoyance**: Getting texts at 10pm asking if the florist contract was signed\n- **Willingness to pay**: $79/month — "worth it if it stops the late-night texts"\n\n### Persona B: Greg - The Systems-Obsessed Coordinator\n- **Age**: 41, male, Denver CO\n- **Weddings/year**: 28 (day-of + partial), lower avg fee but high volume\n- **Current setup**: Elaborate Notion workspace that impresses him but confuses clients\n- **Core pain**: When he hands couples their "planning portal" (a Notion page), they can''t navigate it\n- **Need**: A client view that is foolproof — couples should be able to use it without a tutorial\n- **Willingness to pay**: $49/month for something that just works\n\n### Persona C: The Couples (End-User)\n- **Profile**: Engaged couple, 28-36 years old, planning a wedding 12-18 months out\n- **Expectations**: Real-time visibility, similar to tracking a package\n- **Frustrations**: Having to email their planner to ask what''s been confirmed; not knowing the current budget status\n- **Delight factors**: Beautiful design, mobile-optimized, clear milestone indicators, knowing exactly what decisions still need to be made\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| P0 | Wedding progress hub | Visual milestone tracker (engagement → venue → vendors → ceremony) |\n| P0 | Live task list for couples | Planner assigns to-dos to couples with due dates; couples check off |\n| P0 | Vendor confirmation board | Shows couple which vendors are confirmed, pending, or still needed |\n| P0 | Budget snapshot | High-level budget status (paid / committed / remaining) without line-item detail |\n| P0 | Planner dashboard | Manage all active weddings from one view |\n| P1 | Message thread per wedding | In-app messaging to replace email chains |\n| P1 | Document drop zone | Share contracts, inspiration, floor plans with couples |\n| P1 | Milestone celebration moments | Fun UI moment when a big milestone is hit (venue booked\!) |\n| P1 | Mobile-optimized couple view | Native mobile feel on iOS/Android browsers |\n| P2 | Custom branding | Planner can add their logo, colors, font to the client hub |\n| P2 | Guest list manager | Couple manages RSVPs; planner sees headcount |\n| P2 | Day-of timeline share | Share final timeline with couple and vendors |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n```\nFrontend:\n  - Planner dashboard: React 18 + TailwindCSS\n    - Multi-wedding sidebar\n    - Drag-and-drop milestone reordering\n  - Client portal: Next.js 15 (SSR for shareable URLs)\n    - Optimized for mobile browsers\n    - Accessible via magic link (no login) or optional account\n\nBackend:\n  - Go + Echo v4\n  - WebSocket for real-time task completion notifications\n  - File handling: Cloudflare R2 (cost-effective)\n\nData:\n  - PostgreSQL 16 (weddings, tasks, vendors, budget)\n  - Redis (sessions, WebSocket presence)\n\nAuth:\n  - Planner: email/password + Google SSO\n  - Couple: magic link (no account required)\n\nNotifications:\n  - SendGrid for email digests (weekly progress summary to couples)\n  - Push notifications (P2, via Web Push API)\n```\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Monthly | Annual | Active Weddings | Key Features |\n|------|---------|--------|----------------|-------------|\n| Solo | $39/mo | $390/yr | 12 active | Core hub, 3 clients/month |\n| Pro | $69/mo | $690/yr | 30 active | + custom branding, messaging, docs |\n| Team | $99/mo | $990/yr | Unlimited | + assistant accounts, analytics |\n\n**Monetization principle**: Keep entry price low ($39) to overcome trial resistance; upsell on branding (strong emotional buy for brand-conscious planners) and volume.\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Duration | Focus | Success Criteria |\n|-----------|----------|-------|------------------|\n| M1: Hub core | 5 weeks | Progress hub, task list, vendor board, budget snapshot | 15 beta planners, ≥1 couple using portal |\n| M2: Polish | 3 weeks | Mobile optimization, milestone celebrations, email digests | Couple NPS ≥55 |\n| M3: Communication | 3 weeks | In-app messaging, document sharing | Avg inbound email reduction ≥40% |\n| M4: Monetize | 2 weeks | Billing, plan enforcement, referral program | 40 paying planners |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | Target (6 months) |\n|-----|------------------|\n| Registered planners | 400 |\n| Paid planners | 150 |\n| MRR | $9,000 |\n| Active couple portals | 800 |\n| Avg couple portal logins/week | ≥3 |\n| Planner inbound message reduction | ≥40% |\n| Planner NPS | ≥52 |\n| Couple NPS | ≥58 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Impact | Likelihood | Response |\n|------|--------|------------|----------|\n| Planners don''t invite couples to portal | High | Medium | Onboarding flow makes couple invitation the first mandatory step |\n| Couples prefer texting over portal | Medium | Medium | Weekly email digest pulls couples back; reduce friction with mobile |\n| Feature creep from planner requests | High | High | Strict product roadmap governance; public changelog to set expectations |\n| Aisle Planner copies client portal feature | Medium | Medium | First-mover brand recognition + couple experience depth is hard to copy fast |\n| Seasonal revenue concentration (spring/fall) | Low | High | Offer annual plans; planners book weddings year-round even if events cluster |',
    E'[{"step":"Product framing","decision":"Lead with the client experience angle, not the planner workflow angle","reason":"Client-facing tools are underbuilt in this market; reframing from couple perspective creates differentiation and stronger emotional purchase motivation"},{"step":"Core P0 scoping","decision":"Budget snapshot (not full budget tracker) in client portal","reason":"Couples need reassurance about overall budget health, not line-item detail that creates anxiety; planner retains full view"},{"step":"Auth design","decision":"Magic link for couples, no account required","reason":"Couples use the portal for 12-18 months; mandatory account creation adds friction with no retention benefit for this use case"},{"step":"Pricing","decision":"$39 entry tier","reason":"Lower than Aisle Planner to reduce switching risk perception; solo planners handling 12 weddings/yr are a viable segment at this price"},{"step":"Milestone celebrations","decision":"Add delight moments for milestone completion","reason":"Wedding planning is emotionally charged; positive UX moments differentiate from utilitarian competitors and increase couple engagement"},{"step":"Go-to-market","decision":"Instagram and Pinterest as primary acquisition channels","reason":"Wedding planners are highly active on visual platforms; before/after content showing messy spreadsheet vs. beautiful portal converts well"}]',
    'submitted', 38, NOW() - INTERVAL '17 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '18 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '17 days'),

