(20, 15, E'# ShelfSafe - Expiry Alert System for Independent Pharmacies\n\n## 1. Executive Summary\n\nShelfSafe is a focused expiry management tool for independent pharmacies that turns a labor-intensive monthly manual check into an automated daily monitoring system. The product centers on a simple barcode-scan-and-log workflow that pharmacy technicians can operate in minutes per day, with automated alerts sent 90/60/30/7 days before expiry and auto-generated disposal records formatted for regulatory compliance.\n\n**Mission**: Make expiry compliance the easiest part of running an independent pharmacy.\n\n**Why now**: Increased state board inspection frequency and expanded fine structures since 2022 have made expiry management a top compliance concern for independent pharmacy owners — but the existing tools to manage it are either manual (paper logs) or buried inside expensive pharmacy management systems that small independents cannot afford to upgrade.\n\n## 2. Market Analysis\n\n| Metric | Value | Notes |\n|--------|-------|-------|\n| Independent pharmacies in US | ~22,000 | NCPA 2023 |\n| Avg inventory SKUs | 2,000-5,000 | Mixed OTC + Rx |\n| Avg annual expired drug write-off | $18,000 | Pharmacy Times |\n| FDA/state inspection frequency | 1-3x/year | Varies by state |\n| Typical fine for expired med on shelf | $1,000-$10,000 | State-dependent |\n| Current expiry tool adoption | <12% | Estimate |\n| Industry software spend per pharmacy | $400-$900/mo | Full PMS |\n| Standalone compliance tools TAM | ~$66M/yr | 22k × $3,000 |\n\n**Market dynamic**: Chain pharmacies (CVS, Walgreens) have automated expiry systems built into their enterprise PMS. Independent pharmacies lack equivalent tools, creating a structural compliance gap that regulators are increasingly closing with enforcement.\n\n## 3. Competitive Landscape\n\n| Product | Category | Monthly Cost | Expiry Feature Depth |\n|---------|---------|-------------|---------------------|\n| PioneerRx | Full PMS | $500-$900 | Moderate (not primary feature) |\n| McKesson Pharmacy Systems | Full PMS | $400-$750 | Moderate |\n| Liberty Software | Full PMS | $300-$700 | Basic |\n| Manual paper log | DIY | $0 | Fully manual |\n| Excel/Google Sheets | DIY | $0 | User-maintained |\n| **ShelfSafe** | **Standalone expiry** | **$89-$169** | **Deep (core product)** |\n\n**Positioning**: ShelfSafe is not a PMS replacement — it is a compliance layer that sits alongside any existing PMS. This eliminates the switching cost barrier entirely.\n\n## 4. Target User Personas\n\n### Persona A: Patricia - The Owner-Pharmacist with Inspection Anxiety\n- **Age**: 58, female, rural Kentucky\n- **Pharmacy**: 2,800 SKUs, 35 years in business, 2 part-time techs\n- **Situation**: Had a warning letter from state board 18 months ago for an expired item; now spends $800/month paying a technician to do monthly manual checks\n- **Core need**: Replace the $800/month manual process with a $100/month automated system\n- **Tech comfort**: Low-moderate; comfortable with the pharmacy POS, nervous about new software\n- **Willingness to pay**: $89-$109/month if setup is handled for her\n- **Quote**: "I don''t need anything fancy. I just need to know what''s about to expire before the inspector does."\n\n### Persona B: Marcus - The Efficiency-Focused Young Pharmacist\n- **Age**: 29, male, suburban Atlanta GA\n- **Pharmacy**: Recently acquired independent pharmacy, 3,600 SKUs, modernizing operations\n- **Situation**: Has a spreadsheet from the previous owner that is 3 years out of date and covers maybe 40% of inventory\n- **Core need**: Start from scratch with a proper system; wants scan-at-receiving so the database builds automatically over time\n- **Tech comfort**: High; uses multiple SaaS tools for other parts of the business\n- **Willingness to pay**: $139-$169/month for the full-featured version\n\n### Persona C: The Pharmacy Technician (Direct User)\n- **Profile**: 26-35, female, certified pharmacy tech, 3-6 years experience\n- **Role in purchase**: Not the buyer but primary user; her efficiency determines product success\n- **Needs from the tool**:\n  1. Scanner interface must be fast — she''s scanning while doing 10 other things\n  2. Clear visual cues for expiry urgency (red/yellow/green)\n  3. No training required beyond a 10-minute walkthrough\n- **Frustration with current state**: "I do the expiry check, fill out the paper form, Patricia signs it, then it goes in a binder. No one looks at it until the inspector asks for it."\n\n## 5. Core Features\n\n| Priority | Feature | Description |\n|----------|---------|-------------|\n| P0 | NDC barcode scan + auto-fill | Scan barcode → drug name auto-populates from OpenFDA; enter expiry date |\n| P0 | Expiry alert engine | 90/60/30/7 day alerts via email and in-app |\n| P0 | Today''s expiry checklist | Daily view of all items expiring within 7 days |\n| P0 | Removal log | Log when expired item is removed: date, drug, quantity, lot number |\n| P0 | Compliance report (PDF) | Formatted disposal record for state board inspection |\n| P1 | Color-coded shelf urgency view | Red (<30 days), Yellow (30-90), Green (90+ days) visual list |\n| P1 | Scan-at-receiving mode | Scan items as they arrive; builds database automatically |\n| P1 | Technician accounts | Tech scans and logs; pharmacist reviews alerts and signs off disposals |\n| P1 | Bulk CSV import | Import existing inventory with expiry dates from spreadsheet |\n| P2 | Schedule II separate module | Controlled substance expiry with additional documentation |\n| P2 | Return-to-vendor credit log | Track items returned before expiry and credit received |\n| P2 | Annual write-off summary | Year-end summary of expired inventory cost for accounting |\n\n## 6. Technical Architecture\n\n```\nDesign Philosophy: Tablet-first, fast, offline-capable\n\nFrontend:\n  - React 18 + TailwindCSS (PWA)\n  - Offline mode: IndexedDB for local scan cache; sync when online\n    (Pharmacy internet can be unreliable; offline scanning is critical)\n  - Barcode scanning: Web Serial API (USB scanners) + ZXing (camera)\n  - Print integration: Web Print API for generating paper backup forms\n\nBackend:\n  - Go + Echo v4\n  - NDC lookup: OpenFDA NDC API (rate-limited; cached in Redis)\n  - Expiry check cron: Daily at 6 AM, generates alert queue\n  - PDF generation: Go PDF library (no headless browser dependency)\n\nData:\n  - PostgreSQL 16 (drugs, inventory, expiry records, disposal logs, alerts)\n  - Redis (NDC cache, session, alert queue)\n\nAuth:\n  - Email/password (owner and pharmacist)\n  - PIN-based quick login for technicians at scanning station\n\nNotifications:\n  - SendGrid (daily digest, threshold alerts)\n  - SMS via Twilio (critical: item expiring today or already expired)\n\nData Security:\n  - AES-256 encryption at rest\n  - No patient data — inventory only\n  - Daily encrypted backup to S3\n```\n\n**Offline-first is non-negotiable**: Rural pharmacies often have unreliable internet. The scanning workflow must function completely offline and sync when connectivity returns. This is a hard technical requirement, not an enhancement.\n\n## 7. Business Model\n\n| Plan | Price/mo | SKU Capacity | Users | Key Add-ons |\n|------|----------|-------------|-------|-------------|\n| Essential | $89/mo | 2,500 | 2 | Core scanning, alerts, compliance PDF |\n| Professional | $139/mo | 5,000 | 5 | + Scan-at-receiving, CSV import, color urgency view |\n| Complete | $169/mo | Unlimited | Unlimited | + Schedule II module, return tracking, annual summary |\n| Setup service | $99 one-time | — | — | Remote setup + 30-min staff training call |\n\n**Financial case for pharmacy owners**:\n- RxExpiry cost: $139/month ($1,668/year)\n- Avoided write-offs (60% reduction on $18k avg): $10,800/year\n- Avoided inspection fine (1 fine avoided every 3 years): $4,000/year equivalent\n- Net annual benefit: ~$13,132 vs. $1,668 cost = 8:1 ROI\n\n## 8. MVP Roadmap\n\n| Milestone | Timeframe | Deliverables | Gate |\n|-----------|-----------|-------------|------|\n| M1: Scan + alert | 5 weeks | NDC scan, expiry entry, 30/7 day alerts, removal log | 5 pharmacy beta users |\n| M2: Compliance | 3 weeks | PDF disposal report, technician accounts, CSV import | Report accepted by state board |\n| M3: Workflow | 4 weeks | Scan-at-receiving, color view, offline mode | Technician can use without assistance |\n| M4: Launch | 4 weeks | Billing, NCPA outreach, setup service package | 25 paying pharmacies |\n\n## 9. Success Metrics\n\n| KPI | 3-Month | 6-Month |\n|-----|---------|--------|\n| Registered pharmacies | 40 | 120 |\n| Paid subscribers | 20 | 70 |\n| MRR | $2,200 | $8,500 |\n| Avg items caught before expiry | 5x manual baseline | 8x |\n| Compliance report generation | 100% of removal events | 100% |\n| Inspection outcomes (self-reported) | 0 violations | 0 violations |\n| Pharmacist NPS | ≥55 | ≥65 |\n\n## 10. Risks & Mitigation\n\n| Risk | Severity | Probability | Mitigation |\n|------|----------|-------------|------------|\n| Pharmacy owners resist cloud for drug inventory data | High | High | Clear communication: no patient data; optional local backup; SOC 2 roadmap |\n| Offline sync conflicts (two techs scanning same item offline) | Medium | Medium | Last-write-wins with conflict log; tech confirms on sync |\n| OpenFDA NDC API rate limits | Medium | Medium | Cache NDC lookups for 30 days; manual fallback for unlisted drugs |\n| Low urgency during inspection off-season | Medium | High | Market around inspection season (Q1/Q4 typically); annual plan discounts in fall |\n| PMS vendor bundles improved expiry feature as response | High | Medium | First-mover relationships with NCPA + regional pharmacist associations create defensible distribution |',
    E'[{"step":"Offline-first decision","decision":"Mandatory offline mode with IndexedDB sync","reason":"Rural pharmacies — the highest-pain segment — frequently have unreliable internet; offline capability is a product requirement not a feature enhancement"},{"step":"Positioning","decision":"Complement existing PMS, not replace it","reason":"PMS switching costs are enormous (6-12 months, $10k+ in migration); positioning ShelfSafe as a compliance layer eliminates this barrier and makes the purchase a yes/no decision, not a compete-with-incumbent decision"},{"step":"Technician UX priority","decision":"Technician-optimized scanning interface as primary user flow","reason":"Pharmacist owns the account; technician uses the product daily. If the scanning interface frustrates the tech, the data quality collapses and the product fails"},{"step":"PIN login for techs","decision":"PIN quick-login for scanning station","reason":"Technicians switch tasks constantly; email/password login at a scanning station is a friction point that causes them to skip logging. PIN login takes 2 seconds"},{"step":"ROI framing","decision":"Lead with write-off savings and fine avoidance, not feature comparison","reason":"Independent pharmacy owners are primarily motivated by cost reduction and compliance risk; 8:1 ROI on $1,668/yr investment is a compelling standalone business case"},{"step":"Setup service","decision":"$99 one-time setup service as standard offering","reason":"Low-tech pharmacy owners will abandon self-serve setup; a human onboarding call converts trial to active user and dramatically reduces early churn; $99 covers the cost"}]',
    'draft', 0, NULL, NOW() - INTERVAL '22 days', NOW() - INTERVAL '21 days');

